 Bug-killer working well, host-plant resistance and working well in China 
 David WidawskyaÂ·*, Scott Rozelleb, Songqing Jinb, Jikun Huangc 
 International Rice Research Institute, Social Sciences Division, P.O. Box 933, 1099 Manila, Philippines 
 b Department of Farming-based Money flow, Davis, CA 95616-8512, USA 
 Chinese Center for Farming-based Policy, Chinese College/school of Farming-based Sciences, 30 Baishiqiao Road, Beijing 100081, China 
 a 
 
 c 
 
 Abstract 
 Bug-killers are used as the first (or most important) method of pest control in Asian rice production. Conditions in China have led to demand for 
 high and increasing rice yields, resulting in intensive (producing crops/helping something grow) and adoption of (material that makes plants grow better) (able to reply or react/quick to respond) varieties. The 
 result has been (existing all over a large area) pest (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist). Many studies have guessed bug-killer working well, but few have 
 guessed the working well of other choice methods of pest control, namely host-plant resistance. None have guessed the 
 substitutability between these methods of pest-control. The working well of bug-killers and host-plant resistance, and the 
 substitutability between them is measured using two-stage Cobb-Douglas and translog production functions. Under intensive 
 rice production systems in eastern China, bug-killer working well is low compared to the working well of host-plant resistance. In 
 fact, returns to bug-killer use are negative at the margin. Host-plant resistance is an effective substitute for bug-killers and 
 big reductions in bug-killer use could be (accomplished or gained), with no loss in rice production, through improvements in host-plant 
 resistance. These results suggest that bug-killers are being overused in eastern China and host-plant resistance is being (used much less than expected). Government policies to (help increase/show in a good way) increased bug-killers in rice might be ill (gave opinions about what could or should be done about a situation) given the low working well and 
 negative returns, especially because of well known negative externalities connected with bug-killer use. Â© 1998 Elsevier 
 Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 Keywords: Bug-killers; Host-plant resistance; Chinese rice production 
 
 1. Introduction 
 Farmers around the world are involved in a constant 
 fight, the fight against crop destroying pests. Pests 
 can cause crop damage and reduce farmers' welfare. 
 Luckily, producers can lessen the hits/effects of 
 crop pests, and do so most commonly by applying 
 chemical bug-killers. Reliance on bug-killers as the 
 
 *Corresponding Author. Tel.: +415 8336620, ext. 446; e-mail: 
 d. widawsky@cgnet.com 
 
 0169-5150/98/$19.00 Â© 1998 Elsevier Science B.V. All rights reserved. 
 PII 80169-5150(98)00049-8 
 
 first (or most important) or only means of pest control, however, 
 may not be the most money-making or (able to last/helping the planet) plan, 
 and may have some harmful side effects. In the 
 fight against pests, bug-killers are a double-edged 
 sword. 
 Since the mid-1970s, (people who work to find information) have described 
 unintended results from bug-killer use in farming, especially in developing countries, and a few money-based studies have asked whether 
 current patterns of bug-killer use are (money-based)/cheaply 
 and socially (producing a lot with very little waste). Policy makers in many countries 
 have begun to control bug-killer use, and have taken 
 
 204 
 
 D. Widawsky et al.l Farming-based Money flow 19 (1998) 203-217 
 
 interest in other choice methods for controlling farming-based pests. One method of non-chemical pest control 
 in field crops is the development and spreading around of 
 varieties with host-plant resistance. A resistant crop 
 variety suffers smaller yield losses than non-resistant 
 varieties when subjected to pest (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting). Hostplant resistance may also substitute for and/or complement chemical bug-killers in reducing pest losses 
 and increasing crop yields. 
 The role of host-plant resistance as a pest control 
 other choice raises a few important concerns about 
 commonly watched/followed farming practices. For 
 example, if now available vanetles are 
 already resistant to damaging pests, why do farmers 
 continue to use heavy doses of bug-killers? In the 
 presence of host-plant resistance, do bug-killer-based 
 reductions in pest damage permit the cost of the 
 bug-killer? (related to scientific farming) (event(s) or object(s) that prove something) hints that in some 
 cases they do not; common rates of bug-killer usage 
 may be inefficient in the presence of host-plant resistance (Buntin et al., 1992; Robinson et al., 1978; 
 Teetes, 1994). 
 While studies of bug-killer working well are common, few (people who work to find information) have tested the 
 production hits/effects of host-plant resistance and almost 
 none have explored the interactions between bug-killers and host-plant resistance. The goal of this 
 paper is to Â·analyze the faults/problems of China's bug-killer-intense insect and disease control plans by 
 examining the relative working well of bug-killers and 
 host-plant resistance, and the interactions between 
 them. To meet this goal, the paper first describes 
 the pest management plans used by China's farmers and the (rewards or reasons for doing something) for input intensive rice production that lead to high bug-killer use. The paper then 
 examines the effectiveness of pest control plans 
 on rice production in eastern China, plans based 
 on high levels of insecticide and fungus-killer use as well 
 as adoption of varieties which contain insect and 
 disease resistance. Finally, the paper discusses the 
 possible reasons why farmers apply high rates of 
 bug-killers and do not effectively use host-plant 
 resistance, and the policy effects/results/suggestions of such behavior. 
 To narrow the extent of/the range of the work, the paper 
 addresses pest management practices in two areas 
 of eastern China, Zhejiang and Jiangsu. In order to 
 collect the data necessary to carefully carefully study pest 
 
 control working well, the authors studied the production and management behavior of farmers in China's 
 most important cropping part/area during more than a 
 year of field work, collecting a (like nothing else) set of production, varietal, and pest (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) data at the township 
 level. 
 
 2. (process by which something becomes stronger or worse) of farming and (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) of 
 pests in eastern China 
 Life-giving soil and plentiful water supplies make 
 China's greater Yangtse River Delta area one of 
 the world's most productive rice growing areas. 
 With low per person land availability (Table 1), farmers in the area have usually/(in the past) created some of 
 Asia's highest rice yields through intensive application of labor (Table 1). As the area's population 
 growth has increased pressure on land, pressure has 
 also risen to increase rice yields to face/deal with national 
 concerns of rice independence. Farmers are needed/demanded 
 to sell a big amount of rice production to state 
 purchase (services businesses/government units) (Table 1). Although yield 
 increases are a priority for government leaders, 
 increasing off-farm labor opportunities have reduced labor availability and placed the load for 
 high yields on strengthening the use of (bought) 
 inputs (Table 1). These conditions have caused 
 China's farming-based research system to create, 
 and pushed local leaders and farmers to adopt, modern 
 farming-based technology, including bug-killers (Lin, 
 1992; Huang and Rozelle, 1996). For example, farmers in both Zhejiang and Jiangsu increased their use of 
 chemical (material that makes plants grow better)s at about 5% per year (Widawsky, 
 1996) while increasing their adoption of high-cooperating with/producing/giving up, input-intensive combination rice varieties. 
 2.1. Rising levels of pest (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist) 
 Although pest (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist) have always been a 
 feature of China's rice production, they became a 
 long-lasting problem with the adoption of (material that makes plants grow better) (able to reply or react/quick to respond) varieties, a result/argument from the (related to computers and science) revolution that began in the 1960s and has continued since 
 then (Chengxiang, 1988). Averaging over the four 
 major rice insect pests, the sample areas in Jiangsu 
 and Zhejiang experienced outbreaks about 
 1.5 times in 1985 and nearly two times in 1991 
 
