 the highest in rice producing Asia, just like that 
 of Japan (Edwards, 1986). Among the survey locations in eastern China, five of the eight counties had 
 average rates of insecticide use nearly twice that of 
 lowland watered rice systems in the Philippines, 
 where serious health and (related to surrounding conditions or the health of the Earth) effects 
 have been linked to bug-killer use (Rola and Pingali, 
 1993). 
 
 2.3. (bad results or effects) of intensive bug-killer use 
 With high rates of bug-killer use and the negative 
 externalities connected with such levels, there is a 
 concern about whether bug-killer use has reached 
 levels at which direct not important (things that are given/work that's done) are 
 minor, or maybe even negative. Insecticide sprays 
 early in a rice cropping season have been shown to 
 
 D. Widawsky et al.!Agricultural Money flow 19 (1998) 203-217 
 
 destroy (groups of people/animals/things) of natural deadly animals and cause 
 (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist) of damaging pests such as brown 
 planthopper (Kenmore, 1980; Heinrichs and Mochida, 
 1984; Schoenly et al., 1996). The big thing/the important event of a 
 'pesticide spiral' may happen when heavy bug-killer use 
 in rice results in pest (groups of people/animals/things) that are bug-killer 
 resistant (Chelliah and Heinrichs, 1980). Increasing 
 pest resistance to bug-killers creates a situation in 
 which higher levels of bug-killer are needed to (accomplish or gain with effort) 
 the same level of pest control (Litsinger, 1989). In 
 China, field and laboratory studies have shown that 
 increasing resistance in pest (groups of people/animals/things) to high rates 
 of bug-killer use has decreased the effectiveness of 
 bug-killers (Chu et al., 1987; Su et al., 1991). 
 
 2.4. Host-plant resistance in China 
 While breeding efforts to incorporate host-plant 
 resistance in rice had started in other places, by the late 
 1970s some Chinese rice people (who help animals have babies) were devel- 
 
 207 
 
 oping pest resistant rice varieties. In some areas the 
 presence of resistance was ordered for seed certification. However, given the focus in farming-based 
 planning to development and (act of something getting bigger, wider, etc.) of farm chemicals, host-plant resistance was assigned a secondary 
 role, and adoption of varieties with host-plant resistance was rarely with decreases in bug-killer use. 
 (even though there is the existence of) this secondary status, local (people in charge) 
 extended and farmers in eastern China adopted a wide 
 organized row of rice varieties with host-plant resistance to 
 insects and sicknesses during the period of the survey. 
 On an average, most townships had between three and 
 nine pest resistant varieties planted by farmers 
 (Widawsky, 1996). Even with these resistant varieties, 
 producers in the study area continued to use bug-killers 
 at rates high enough that they may have added/have given to 
 a (worsening / rusting, crumbling, etc.) of the resistance (at first/before other things happened) included in 
 the newly released varieties. A big proportion 
 of spread around varieties grown during the 1984-1991 study 
 
