 period, experienced breaking down host-plant resistance 
 (Table 2)? Among varieties with broken-down hostplant resistance, the importance of resistance decline is 
 big, averaging 25%-35% decline for all pests 
 (Table 2). The average decline in resistance among all 
 varieties, both those with and without broken-down 
 host-plant resistance, is still large amounts of and raises 
 concerns about China's ability to maintain current 
 levels of host-plant resistance in its rice cultivars 
 (Table 2). 
 While host-plant resistance should aid in the struggle to maintain high yields by (making small) pest 
 damage, the process of breeding for insect and disease 
 resistance may be connected with lower yield potentials. A yield/resistance tradeoff may arise because 
 host-plant resistance is commonly strongest in landraces or other cultivars with lower maximum-(able to be done or reached) yields (Khush, 1987), and their including into 
 modem rice cultivars adds (related to tiny chemical assembly instructions inside of living things) material from land 
 races that may reduce yields. Back-crossing using 
 high-cooperating with/producing/giving up varieties can (make small) this trade-off, 
 but farming-based (people in charge) in eastern China pointed to/showed 
 this had not always been completely successful. 
 
 3. Modelling pest control in China 
 The discussion above raises a few important questions about the effectiveness of pest control practices 
 in China. Does applying bug-killers in rice permit their 
 use at current rates, especially in the presence of 
 improved varieties with host-plant resistance? Is 
 host-plant resistance a productive input in rice production? Can host-plant resistance effectively substitute for bug-killers as a form of pest control? 
 Answering these questions needs/demands measuring the 
 working well of both bug-killers and host-plant resis2 A way of measuring pest resistance for rice varieties grown in eastern 
 China is based on (in other countries) recognized methods of testing-related 
 pest resistance in rice (International Rice Research Institute, 1979). 
 Varieties that show some level of resistance are assigned a 
 (done or made to look the same way every time) resistance index based on their (chance of being harmed) (or lack 
 of it). In the study area in eastern China, the resistance scale ranged 
 from 0 to 5 and was based on judging requirements in government published 
 handbooks. Resistance data were collected from seed company and 
 plant protection departments at each location for varieties grown in 
 that location, and the status of resistant varieties was watched and followed/made footprints of over 
 time for each of six major pests. 
 
 tance, as well as measuring the tradeoff between the 
 two. This section outlines the scientific (solid basic structure on which bigger things can be built) for 
 carefully studying pest control in China, describes the data, 
 and presents results from the analysis. 
 Modelling pest control presents a challenge for 
 a few reasons. To guess their working well, measures of both chemical bug-killers and host-plant resistance need to be included in the analysis. To our 
 knowledge, no previous study has tried to treat 
 host-plant resistance as a directly measured input. 
 There are complex interactions between pest (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist) and crop yields, and model (detailed description of exactly what is required) must be 
 (good or well enough) flexible to include limits/guidelines for interactions and substitutability. The use of bug-killers by 
 farmers and their effectiveness may also depend on the 
 level of pest (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting). For fair and (producing a lot with very little waste) 
 guesses of the hit/effect of bug-killer inputs on yields, 
 the frequency and extreme harshness of pest outbreaks need to be 
 taken into the process of carefully thinking about something. 
 
 3.1. Functional forms and scientific (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) 
 The Cobb-Douglas production function has often 
 been used to guess bug-killer working well, but has 
 two faults/problems. The ability to stretch of substitution 
 between host-plant resistance and bug-killer (and 
 among all other inputs) is held back to be identically 
 equal to one, and a standard Cobb-Douglas model 
 does not account for the possible endogeneity of 
 bug-killers. If bug-killers are applied in response to pest 
 pressure, and high levels of (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist) are related 
 to lower yields, then a relationship between bug-killers 
 and negative extras/payments in a production function might 
 bias working well guesses for bug-killer and host-plant 
 resistance. 
 To scientifically account for these factors, the first 
 modelling approach used in this analysis can be 
 specified as a two-stage Cobb-Douglas models with 
 interaction terms. The first stage to be guessed is a 
 log-linearized huge function for bug-killer 
 use: 
