 3.2. Data 
 
 The data come from a variety of sources in (away from cities) 
 China, and were collected by the authors during nearly 
 one year of (work done by traveling to a place to watch, listen, learn, etc.) in 1993. Township-level data 
 come from eight randomly selected townships in 
 each of the eight counties (for a total of 64 townships) 
 in Jiangsu and Zhejiang areas and were available 
 for eight years, 1984-1991. While most information 
 came from standard data reporting and (related to studying numbers) 
 collection sources, the written records of pest control 
 technicians from the 64 townships given information for (like nothing else) measures of bug-killer inputs, pest 
 (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist), pest damage, and the level of pest-resistance for each variety. Rice yield was measured in 
 kg ha - 1 and explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) were specified as 
 follows. 
 Bug-killers: This study uses three common ways of doing things for measuring bug-killer use: real money-based value 
 (yuanlha), total/totally/with nothing else mixed in active ingredient (kg a.i./ha), and 
 
 210 
 
 D. Widawsky et at./Agricultural Money flow 19 (1998) 203-217 
 
 strength-(changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) or 'effective' amounts where active 
 ingredient was (done or made to look the same way every time) by a recommended dose 
 for each bug-killer. Measures of all the three are 
 used for both insecticides and disease-control 
 bug-killers using described/explained bug-killer data collected in 
 each township; 
 Host-plant resistance: Each variety grown in each 
 location is assigned resistance scores (for 3 year 
 periods of time (or space)) to each of the four insects and two sicknesses 
 using a five-point scale (with higher scores being 
 connected with higher resistance). Variety-specific 
 resistance data are weighted in two ways. First, since 
 high resistance to a certain insect does not insure 
 resistance to all insects, pest-clearly stated/particular resistance 
 is weighted by the (number of times something happens) of that pest in the 
 township, giving more weight to resistance against 
 the most long-lasting pests. Second, since widely spread around 
 varieties (use/put into action) greater influence on township-level 
 yield than poorly spread around varieties, proportion of 
 spread around area in each variety is used to weigh varietyspecific insect and disease resistance, giving more 
 weight to cultivars that rule a township's varietal 
 mix. 
 Pest pressure: The proportion of total spread around area 
 (filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) by a given insect or disease is an indicator of 
 the extent of pest pressure. (number of times something happens) of multiple 
 bug-killer treatments is included as a measure of the 
 extreme harshness of a pest (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting). 
 Other factors: Chemical (material that makes plants grow better) is included 
 as a total/totally/with nothing else mixed in nutrient amount of both nitrogen and 
 phosphorous (i.e. kg total/totally/with nothing else mixed in N/ha). Labor is measured 
 as the ratio of available laborers to total (helped to grow) 
 area (and showed strong positive relationship with 
 (related to a local area) guesses of per hectare labor use, as 
 listed in the state price (government agency/chest of drawers)'s cost of 
 production data). Machinery input is the proportion 
 of (helped to grow) area plowed by mechanical tractor. 
 Time is a substitute for technical change. The proportion 
 of double-cropping represents the influence of a 
 shorter growing season compared to single-season 
 rice production. A dummy (number or thing that changes) for (related to the Earth's weather) 
 disasters (e.g. a major flood in Gaoyou in 1991) 
 accounts for major production shocks. Purchase responsibilities quotas (in kg ha- 1) in bug-killer 
 (statement about the future) equations measure policy pressure to create high yields through the use of bug-killers. Fixedeffects, or county-specific dummy (numbers that change/things that change), account 
 for (related to space or existing in space) differences. The data are summarized by 
 
 their mean and standard moving away in Widawsky 
 (1996). 
 
 4. Results 
 Eqs. (1) and (2) were guessed as specified. 
 The two-stage translog model (Eqs. (1) and (4)) 
 produced different guesses, where some interaction terms were restricted to reduce multicolinearity.4 For each model, three guesses are received/got 
 going along with/matching up to the different methods for measuring 
 bug-killers. 5 
 The general performance of the yield function 
 guesses is fairly strong relating to/connected to bug-killer 
 (detailed description of exactly what is required) and yield function (Table 3). The 
 R2 -values of the guessed yield functions change/differ 
 from 0.53 to 0.59. Because conditions in eastern 
 China focus on high produces and input use, one 
 might expect that the high rate at which the usual inputs are used leads to low not important productivities. The working well of (material that makes plants grow better), labor, and 
 machinery are usually quite low, but are almost the same 
 to those found in other studies of intensive rice 
 (producing crops/helping something grow) in Asia, in general (Pingali et al., 
 1995b), and China in particular (Putterman and 
 Chiacu, 1994).6 
 Limit/guideline guesses from the bug-killer (statement about the future) 
 equations (show or prove) that bug-killer use is related 
 to rate of (situation where something is filled with lots of something harmful or disgusting) of both insects and sicknesses 
 (Table 4). Moving backward coefficients ranged from 0.42 
 to 0.57 for the insecticide equations and from 0.30 to 
 0.35 for the fungus-killer equations. Tests of endogeneity 
 4 Since there are four pest control inputs and four (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy) inputs, 
 there are possibly 36 interaction terms alone which makes 
 guess (unlikely/not capable of being done). Therefore, the interaction which were not 
 restricted to be equal to zero were: squared pest control terms, 
 squared (usual/ commonly and regular/ healthy)-input terms, insecticide* (insect resistance), 
 fungus-killer(disease resistance), and all nitrogen* (pest control 
 input) interactions. 
 5 Full moving backward summaries are given in Widawsky, 1996. 
 6 The other explanatory (numbers that change/things that change) in the yield equations all had 
 expected hits/effects on yield. The positive coefficient on the time 
 (number or thing that changes) supports the idea that (related to computers and science) progress happened 
 during the survey period, and is agreeing with/matching up with/working regularly with other studies of rice 
 yields in China (Huang and Rozelle, 1996). Double-cropping is 
 connected with lower produces, the result of shorter growing seasons. 
 The coefficient on the (numbers that change/things that change) representing stormy weather 
 years is (in an expected way/in a way that was known beforehand) negative in all cases. 
 
 D. Widawsky et al./Agricultural Money flow 19 (1998) 203-217 
 
 reject the simple Cobb-Douglas model in which 
 bug-killers are assumed to be (coming from the outside of something)? Models of 
 rice yield that do not account for the relationship 
 between bug-killers, pest (situations where large numbers of harmful or disgusting things exist), and rice yields 
 may create (created unfair thinking in)/(unfair-thinking) guesses of pest control working well. Therefore, while some coefficient guesses 
 from the simple Cobb-Douglas functions are almost the same 
 to those of the other yield functions, we will (focus and increase) the rest of our attention on guesses came/coming from 
 the models where bug-killers are endogenous. 
 
 4.1. Guesses of bug-killer working well 
 Working well of bug-killers as measured by ability to stretch 
 of production, and allocative (wasting very little while working or producing something) as measured 
 by the ratio of value not important product of bug-killer to 
 the price of bug-killers suggest that farmers in China 
 are overusing chemical pest control methods 
 
 7 Endogeneity of bug-killers was tested using Hausman (1978) 
 method. The test is run by guessing the two-stage Cobb-Douglas 
 yield function with both (described the future) and actual bug-killer levels and 
 testing whether the coefficients on both (described the future) insecticide and 
 fungus-killer are both/together zero (an F-test). For value-based measures of 
 bug-killers the F-value was 4.18, for active ingredient based 
 measures it was 6.02, and for effective or strength-based measures 
 the F-value was 1.91. The first two tests comfortably reject the null 
 guess that bug-killers are (coming from the outside of something), and the last test is 
 somewhat less convincing. Exogeneity of (tools or objects used to do work or measure something) was tested 
 with Hausman (1983) method which simplifies to moving backward the 
 extras/payments from Eq. (2) on the (tools or objects used to do work or measure something). A low R2 -value hints 
 that the error is not related to the explanatory (tools or objects used to do work or measure something). A 
 high R2 -value rejects the null guess of no relationship (e.g. 
 exogeneity). The test statistic is IVR2 , where N is the number of 
 (instances of watching, noticing, or making statements). The test-statistic is distributedchi as (chi-squared 
 with 2 degrees of freedom, and had values of 11.46, 11.41, and 
 18.13 for the value-based, pure, and effective (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) of 
 bug-killer, (match up each pair of items in order). The second nested (null) guess is that 
 there is no difference between the two-stage Cobb-Douglas and 
 translog models. Testing the null guess that there is no 
 difference between the models is carried out by both/together testing 
 whether all the interaction terms are equal to zero, a standard Ftest. In the guesses using value-based and active-ingredient based 
 bug-killers, the test statistics reject, with 99% confidence, the 
 guess that the two-stage Cobb-Douglas and translog (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) are the same (F=2.102 and 2.2716, (match up each pair of items in order)). For the 
 model using strength-(changed to make better/changed to fit new conditions) active ingredient, the test-statistic is 
 F= 1.354 and rejects the null guess less convincingly at 83% 
 confidence. In spite of this, there is not too much difference 
 between the two (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) in guesses of bug-killer working well, host-plant resistance working well, or elasticities of substitution, 
 as the next section shows. 
 
 211 
 
 (Table 5). 8 Small and significant production ability to stretch 
 for insecticide (and even negative in the case of 
 fungus-killers) point to/show that producers receive low returns 
 at the margin. Bug-killer use is allocatively inefficient 
 in so far as added/more bug-killer use creates costs 
 greater than the returns from higher yields. If bug-killers have negative net returns in production, and the 
 externalities of bug-killer use (which are not included) 
 have been shown to increase costs even further (as 
 shown in Rola and Pingali, 1993), then these results 
 may aid in creating future policies that reduce the 
 use of chemical bug-killers. 
 
 4.2. Guesses of host-plant resistance working well 
 Working well of host-plant resistance to insects, as 
 measured by its production ability to stretch, is positive for all 
 (detailed descriptions of exactly what is required) of the production models (Table 5). 
 These results show that host-plant resistance is effective at the margin in controlling insects. More than that, 
 money-based returns to improving host-plant resistance 
 may be big. One rough way to calculate the 
 value of host-plant resistance to insects in the two 
 study areas is to suppose a modest 1% increase in 
 host-plant resistance and use production elasticities to 
 calculate the value of the increase in rice production 
 that would result. The value of the increase in Zhejiang 
 and Jiangsu would range from$ 281 000 to$ 1.49 million. 9 These calculations do not take into account 
 supply responses and price effects from increased 
 production. Rather, they are a (experience-based thinking) device to 
 broadly define the high levels of direct benefits from 
 small improvements in host-plant resistance. In fact, 
 these benefits are big when compared to the 
 about $_$ 1.5 million per year that is spent on 
 all rice research in four areas in eastern China, 
 including Zhejiang and Jiangsu (Rozelle et al., 1996). 
 Resistance to sicknesses had negative guessed hits/effects 
 (a somewhat surprising result that may be 
 related to both the fast (worsening / rusting, crumbling, etc.) of the effective- 
 
