 from an improvement in host-plant resistance may well outweigh 
 the costs, and at the same time (in a big way) reduce negative 
 externalities from bug-killer use. 
 
 5. Discussion and ends/end results 
 Bug-killer use is high in eastern China, a result of money-based and policy pressures to raise 
 yields by strengthening input use. The difference 
 between (possible greatness or power) and actual crop loss might lead 
 one to decide that China's bug-killer-first policy 
 has been successful, a statistic often referred to by government leaders as the basis for continuing pro-bug-killer 
 policies. This paper has shown, however, that although 
 bug-killers may reduce crop losses on average, they are 
 probably being overused in Chinese rice production 
 while host-plant resistance is being under-used. All 
 
