 guesses show that current rates of bug-killer use are 
 allocatively inefficient at the margin, connoting inefficiency even without other issues such as 
 negative externalities. 
 Why are farmers overusing bug-killers? One reason 
 may be that farmers lack good information about the 
 working well of bug-killers. Studies in the Philippines 
 (Pingali et al., 1995a), Vietnam (Heong et al., 1994), 
 and in other places in Asia have shown that after farmers 
 received information about the true working well of 
 bug-killers in rice production, they decreased their use 
 of bug-killer, often very much so. Another argument 
 raised in trying to create agreement between negative returns to producers is that since farmers may be risk disliking, and 
 
 bug-killers may help reduce the risk of very bad 
 pest loss, the seen/obvious money-based inefficiency is, in 
 fact, only a clear risk higher cost and not money-based 
 inefficiency at all. Some of the studies referred to above, 
 however, have shown that ending of bug-killer use 
 has happened with no dangerous increase in yield 
 (quality of changing over time or at different places). Even if farmers are risk disliking, reducing 
 bug-killer use may not increase doubt. 
 The results also show that host-plant resistance, 
 especially insect resistance, is a productive, (used much less than expected) input. Benefits from improvements in hostplant resistance may be quite large. As a substitute for 
 bug-killers, improvements in host-plant resistance 
 could lead to big savings in bug-killers without 
 
